[Student "S"]
{You have an easy choice, you open 1\S.

Partner responds 1NT.  

Partner is showing 6-10 points. With 17 points you are strong enough to invite game. You show your 6-card suit by jumping to 3\S. Partner bids 4\S.

North plays 4\S. East leads the \CQ.

<b>North plays 4\S. East leads the \CQ.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 2 : \D 1 : \C 1 : Total = 4

You have no time to waste. You have no way to discard either minor suit loser, so you absolutely must ruff a \H in dummy. You dare not pull a trump. Win the \CA in dummy and play a \H to your \HQ. East will win and probably lead a trump. You win, cash the \HK and ruff your small \H with dummy's last trump. Now take the \DA and give up the lead. Ruff at the first opportunity and pull trumps, making 6 \S tricks, 2 minor suit Aces, one \H trick and a \H ruff in dummy.

It's easy to decide whether to draw trumps or not.

Always draw them - unless you have some other need for them first. Like in this hand.

Notice this. You cannot fault East for his opening lead, top of an honor sequence is very logical. <b>BUT</b>, if he had led a trump you would have gone down.}
[Play "W"]CQ

