[Student "S"]
{You open 1\S. Partner responds 2\S. What is your bid? 

This was easy. You had a minimum opening bid and partner gave a minimum response. You pass.

South plays 2\S. West leads the \HQ.

<b>South plays 2\S. West leads the \HQ, East plays \H9.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 1 : \D 3 : \C 2 : Total = 6

You have one loser too many. It doesn't seem you can do anything about the 3 \Ds but you might be able to avoid one of the \Cs if you are lucky. However, you can probably get rid of the \H loser by ruffing it in dummy. 

One small worry - East's play of the \H9 might be the start of a doubleton signal. If so, he may be able to over-ruff dummy. You should have played the \HA on the first trick. Next you pull two rounds of trumps with \SA, \SK. Only then do you play \HK and \H8 ruffing with dummy's last trump. Fortunately East only had two trumps and cannot over-ruff, even though he is out of \Hs.

When you get back in you will pull trumps and lead toward dummy's \C K J, hoping to make a good guess.

As you see, the \C A Q were sitting badly and you could not win a \C trick.

The only way to make the contract was to ruff a \H in dummy. }
[Play "W"]HQ

